    <section class="faq-section">
        <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

        <details>
            <summary>What defines a growth stock?</summary>
            <p style="margin-top: 0.5rem; line-height: 1.6;">Growth stocks are companies expected to grow their sales and earnings at a significantly faster rate than the market average. They typically reinvest all their profits back into the business rather than paying dividends, resulting in higher volatility but greater capital appreciation potential.</p>
        </details>

        <details>
            <summary>Why are interest rates so important for growth stocks?</summary>
            <p style="margin-top: 0.5rem; line-height: 1.6;">Growth stocks derive much of their valuation from future expected earnings. When interest rates rise, the present value of those future earnings decreases, causing valuation multiples to contract. Conversely, lowering rates often acts as a massive tailwind for growth stocks.</p>
        </details>

        <details>
            <summary>What is the 'Rule of 40' in software?</summary>
            <p style="margin-top: 0.5rem; line-height: 1.6;">The Rule of 40 is a benchmark used to evaluate SaaS (Software as a Service) companies. It states that a company's revenue growth rate plus its free cash flow margin should equal or exceed 40%. It balances the trade-off between aggressive growth and profitability.</p>
        </details>

        <details>
            <summary>How does AI impact these growth projections?</summary>
            <p style="margin-top: 0.5rem; line-height: 1.6;">AI is the biggest secular growth driver of this decade. It acts as a massive catalyst for semiconductor companies, cloud infrastructure providers, and software platforms that can successfully integrate generative AI to enhance productivity and raise prices.</p>
        </details>

        <details>
            <summary>Are growth stocks riskier than value stocks?</summary>
            <p style="margin-top: 0.5rem; line-height: 1.6;">Generally, yes. Growth stocks often trade at high valuations based on optimistic future projections. If a company misses earnings estimates or growth slows even slightly, the stock price can suffer severe multiple compression.</p>
        </details>

    </section>
